{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} {{BLP sources|date=September 2011}} '''Hector L. MacQueen''', [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]], [[Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]], (born 1956) is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] academic, a senior scholar of [[Scots law]] and [[legal history]], and member of the [[Scottish Law Commission]]. He is [[Professor]] of [[Private law|Private Law]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/smgpubs/access/528285611.html?dids=528285611:528285611&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+23%2C+2004&author=Lucy+Adams+and%3B+Murray+Ritchie&pub=The+Herald&desc=Lord+advocate+'crossed+line+into+politics'%3B+Colin+Boyd+accused+of+compromising+independence&pqatl=google|title=Lord advocate 'crossed line into politics'; Colin Boyd accused of compromising independence|last=Adams|first=Lucy|author2=Murray Ritchie |date=23 January 2004|work=Glasgow Herald|page=6|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> and a former Dean of its [[University of Edinburgh School of Law|Faculty of Law]]. He is author, co-author and editor of a large number books on Scottish law and legal history, including the 11th, 12th, 13th and 14th editions of the standard text ''Gloag & Henderson Law of Scotland'', and is former Literary Director of the [[Stair Society]]. [[Stetson University College of Law]], Florida, appointed him Distinguished International Professor 2007-2009, and he taught European Copyright Law there. As an historian, he has a particular interest in the law and society of medieval [[Carrick, Scotland|Carrick]] and [[Galloway]]. He is currently a member of the International Advisory Group for the JKLH-funded project, 'The Paradox of Medieval Scotland, 1093-1286'. In 1995 he became a Fellow of [[Royal Society of Edinburgh|The Royal Society of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rse.org.uk/fellow/hector-macqueen/|title=Professor Hector Lewis MacQueen FBA FRSE - The Royal Society of Edinburgh|work=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en-GB}}</ref>
